<div class="patternContent"><div class="patternTopic"> <h1><a name="Security_Exercises_Understand_yo"></a> Security Exercises - Understand your certificate </h1>
<p />
This exercise will give you some understanding of your x.509 certificate
<p />
<div class="twikiToc"> <ul>
<li> <a href="?cover=print#Security_Exercises_Understand_yo"> Security Exercises - Understand your certificate</a> <ul>
<li> <a href="?cover=print#Environment"> Environment</a>
</li> <li> <a href="?cover=print#Exercise_1_OpenSSL"> Exercise 1 - OpenSSL</a>
</li> <li> <a href="?cover=print#Exercise_2_Creating_a_proxy"> Exercise 2 - Creating a proxy</a>
</li> <li> <a href="?cover=print#Exercise_3_Creating_a_VOMS_exten"> Exercise 3 - Creating a VOMS-extended proxy</a>
</li></ul> 
</li></ul> 
</div>
<p />
<h2 class="twikinetRoundedAttachments"><span class="twikinetHeader"><a name="Environment"></a> Environment </span></h2>
<p />
We will use the usual node:<br>
<code>vdt-itb.cs.wisc.edu</code>
<p />
<h2 class="twikinetRoundedAttachments"><span class="twikinetHeader"><a name="Exercise_1_OpenSSL"></a> Exercise 1 - OpenSSL </span></h2>
<p />
You should have your DOEGrids-issues certificate in:<br>
<code>~/.globus/</code>.
<p />
You have two files: <ul>
<li> <code>usercert.pem</code> - This is the public part of the certificate. It contains the description of the certificate, including the public key, but does not contain not the private key.
</li> <li> <code>userkey.pem</code> -  This file contains the private key of the certificate. <strong>Keep it secret!</strong>
</li></ul> 
<p />
You can peek at the content of the certificate, using <a href="http://www.openssl.org/docs/apps/x509.html" target="_top">openssl</a>. It is installed on most Linux systems by default.
<p />
Try it out. 
<p />
The most complete output is obtained using the <code>-text</code> flag, but others are useful as well.
<p />
What do you see?
<p />
<div class="twistyPlugin twikiMakeVisibleInline">  <span id="twistyIdEducationOSGSS2011TueSecurityEx11show" class="twistyStartHide twistyTrigger twikiUnvisited twistyInited0"><a href="#"><img src="/twiki/pub/TWiki/TWikiDocGraphics/toggleopen-small.gif" border="0" alt="" /><span class="twikiLinkLabel twikiUnvisited">Next step</span></a> </span> <span id="twistyIdEducationOSGSS2011TueSecurityEx11hide" class="twistyStartHide twistyTrigger twikiUnvisited twistyHidden twistyInited0"><a href="#"><img src="/twiki/pub/TWiki/TWikiDocGraphics/toggleclose-small.gif" border="0" alt="" /><span class="twikiLinkLabel twikiUnvisited">Hide</span></a> </span>  </div><!--/twistyPlugin twikiMakeVisibleInline--> <div class="twistyPlugin"><div id="twistyIdEducationOSGSS2011TueSecurityEx11toggle" class="twistyStartHide twistyContent twikiMakeHidden twistyInited0">
One of the things you should have seen, is that the cert was issued by DOEGrids CA.
<p />
The CA public certificates are pre-installed in <code>/etc/grid-security/certificates/</code>.<br>
Each CA has a set of files, with *.0 being the certificate.
<p />
The files are encoded using a SSL-internal scheme. You can find the right name under the your certificate "CRL Distribution" section.
<p />
Run openssl against the DOEGrids certificate.<br>
What do you see?
</div></div> <!--/twistyPlugin--> 
<p />
<p />
<h2 class="twikinetRoundedAttachments"><span class="twikinetHeader"><a name="Exercise_2_Creating_a_proxy"></a> Exercise 2 - Creating a proxy </span></h2>
<p />
To create a proxy, you have to use the globus tools that are part of the <a href="https://twiki.grid.iu.edu/bin/view/ReleaseDocumentation/UserCESimpleTest#Authentication_using_a_Grid_Prox" target="_top">OSG client installation</a>.
<p />
For starters, try out <code>grid-proxy-init</code>. This will create a proxy for for you.
<p />
To check the status of the proxy, use <code>grid-proxy-info</code>.
<p />
Try it. <br>
What do you see?
<p />
<div class="twistyPlugin twikiMakeVisibleInline">  <span id="twistyIdEducationOSGSS2011TueSecurityEx12show" class="twistyStartHide twistyTrigger twikiUnvisited twistyInited0"><a href="#"><img src="/twiki/pub/TWiki/TWikiDocGraphics/toggleopen-small.gif" border="0" alt="" /><span class="twikiLinkLabel twikiUnvisited">Show tips</span></a> </span> <span id="twistyIdEducationOSGSS2011TueSecurityEx12hide" class="twistyStartHide twistyTrigger twikiUnvisited twistyHidden twistyInited0"><a href="#"><img src="/twiki/pub/TWiki/TWikiDocGraphics/toggleclose-small.gif" border="0" alt="" /><span class="twikiLinkLabel twikiUnvisited">Hide</span></a> </span>  </div><!--/twistyPlugin twikiMakeVisibleInline--> <div class="twistyPlugin"><div id="twistyIdEducationOSGSS2011TueSecurityEx12toggle" class="twistyStartHide twistyContent twikiMakeHidden twistyInited0">
<p />
One obvious thing to change is the proxy lifetime. Try the <code>-valid</code> option.
<p />
You can also change the location of the proxy, by either using the <code>-out</code> option, or by setting X509_USER_PROXY.
</div></div> <!--/twistyPlugin--> 
<p />
<h2 class="twikinetRoundedAttachments"><span class="twikinetHeader"><a name="Exercise_3_Creating_a_VOMS_exten"></a> Exercise 3 - Creating a VOMS-extended proxy </span></h2>
<p />
As explained during the lecture, OSG requires VOMS attributes to authorize you at Grid sites.
<p />
To create a proxy, you have to use the VOMS tools that are part of the 
<a href="https://twiki.grid.iu.edu/bin/view/ReleaseDocumentation/UserCESimpleTest#Authentication_using_a_VOMS_Prox" target="_top">OSG client installation</a>.
<p />
The tool to use is <code>voms-proxy-init</code>. It works very similarly to <code>grid-proxy-init</code>, you just need to add the VOMS attribute you want to get.
In our case we will use:<br>
<code>-voms osgedu:/osgedu/2011OSGSummerSchool</code>
<p />
To check the status of the proxy, use <code>voms-proxy-info</code>.
<p />
Try it. <br>
What do you see?
<p />
As usual, the two commands have plenty of options. Try them out.
<p />
<div class="twistyPlugin twikiMakeVisibleInline">  <span id="twistyIdEducationOSGSS2011TueSecurityEx13show" class="twistyStartHide twistyTrigger twikiUnvisited twistyInited0"><a href="#"><img src="/twiki/pub/TWiki/TWikiDocGraphics/toggleopen-small.gif" border="0" alt="" /><span class="twikiLinkLabel twikiUnvisited">Show tips</span></a> </span> <span id="twistyIdEducationOSGSS2011TueSecurityEx13hide" class="twistyStartHide twistyTrigger twikiUnvisited twistyHidden twistyInited0"><a href="#"><img src="/twiki/pub/TWiki/TWikiDocGraphics/toggleclose-small.gif" border="0" alt="" /><span class="twikiLinkLabel twikiUnvisited">Hide</span></a> </span>  </div><!--/twistyPlugin twikiMakeVisibleInline--> <div class="twistyPlugin"><div id="twistyIdEducationOSGSS2011TueSecurityEx13toggle" class="twistyStartHide twistyContent twikiMakeHidden twistyInited0">
<p />
There are two interesting options of <code>voms-proxy-info</code>: <ul>
<li> <code>-all</code> - You have to specify this to see the VOMS attributes. Without, it works pretty much just <code>grid-proxy-info</code>.
</li> <li> <code>-chain</code> - Shows you all the chain up to the originating CA.
</li></ul> 
<p />
Try them out.
</div></div> <!--/twistyPlugin--> 
<p />
You may have noticed you used voms-proxy-init for the exercises this morning. Well... now you know what it was used for.</div><!-- /patternTopic-->
<p />
<p />
